Security operatives yesterday took over parts of Port Harcourt City  and Obio/Akpor local government areas of Rivers State, as the state government imposed a 24-hour curfew on the affected areas. LEADERSHIP observed that the security operatives include soldiers, police and Nigerian Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC), the Nigerian Air Force and Department of State Service (DSS). They barricaded major roads leading to Education Bus Stop to Agip Junction, Ikwerre Road, in Port Harcourt City local government area as well as Obiri Ikwerre Junction to Ozuoba, Rumualogu and Choba, in Ohio/Akpor local government area. Commuters in the affected areas were stranded as commercial vehicles were not allowed to operate while residents were forced to raise their hands up while walking along the streets. LEADERSHIP recalls that Governor Nyesom Ezenwo Wike had, in a statewide broadcast on Monday, declared a dusk-to-dawn curfew in the affected areas following the decision of the State Security Council to that effect. However, residents of the state woke up to see large number of security operatives on the affected areas. Announcing the imposition of the 24-hour curfew, the commissioner for Information and Communications, Pastor Paulinus Nsirim, said the action was in the state government’s quest to prevent spread of the coronavirus in the state.